description: While enjoying a visit to Muir Woods, I noticed this 3-leaf clover-like plant growing in various places, at the foot of most of the tree trunks.  The leaves were between 1-2 inches wide, and a vibrant color of green.  The leaves grew a height of approximately 2-2.5 inches.
On all my visits to Muir Woods, in 2010, I noticed the entire floor of the woods was covered with these fern. They varied in size, both in height and width.
Saw these fungi growing on a dead/fallen over tree (branch), while touring Muir Woods National Monument.  The width of each squiggly plate was approximately 4-5 inches.
Saw these fungi growing on a living tree, while touring Muir Woods National Monument.  Each plate was approximately 5 inches in width, and 2-3 inches in thickness.
Saw these fungi growing on the edge of a dead/fallen over tree, while touring Muir Woods National Monument.  Each plate was approximately 8 inches in width, and perhaps 1-2 inches in thickness.
Saw these fungi growing on the underside of a dead tree, while touring Muir Woods National Monument.  Appearance was slimy and pale in color, and growth was approximately 2-3 feet in width.

description:
Male and female found in the same web mass under an old log. Both were collected and after some guidance the female was identified as C. angelena using Chamberlin and Ivie's 1941 revision.

The clincher was the long scape (or stylus in Chamberlin and Ivie 1941) on the epigynum - a defining feature of the genus. It was very close to both C. restricta and C. angelena, but the stylus is white in restricta and dark in angelena. C. angelena has also been found in California while restricta has not (supporting point).
According to the revision, members of this genus are very close in appearance to Agelenopsis, requiring a detailed look at the spider's reproductive structures to distinguish them. Interestingly, the male has never been formally described.

Death Cap, Amanita phalloides, Walnut Creek, California I was surprised to see these growing in a big grass lawn since I usually find them in oak leaf litter, but there was an oak tree around that they may have been associating with. Note the white gills, the skirt on the stalk and the vulva (bulb) on the bottom of the stalks. Also the sickly greenish tinge to the caps. The alpha-amanitin toxin from the death cap acts by blocking mRNA synthesis. It binds to and restricts the bridge helix of RNA Pol II involved in DNA translocation, so basically you end up with cells that can't produce the message that allows you to make proteins that make your cells work. Here is the paper for the structural fitting of the toxin into RNA Polymerase II: www.pnas.org/content/99/3/1218.full The RNA Pol II from Aminita family mushrooms isn't susceptible to the toxins (obviously), either is Agaricus bisporus (common store mushroom), but yeast and water molds are and most other Euks. The amanitin toxins are found all over the mushroom, but most concentrated at the hymenium (~gills) and in the cap. At the cellular level the toxins appear to be compartmentalized and not evenly distributed in the cells of a specific tissue. The toxins are produced on the ribosomes! .. and then go through further modification to reach their final state: ec.asm.org/cgi/reprint/EC.00161-10v1.pdf

description: Encountering all three species of newt within a meter of each other was a piece of luck! This shot shows another way to tell apart Taricha torosa and T. granulosa: in the former, the yellow coloration extends right up to the eye, and in the latter the dark coloration tends to extend below the eye. Stebbins actually says you should check the color of the lower eyelid, which seems somewhat absurd, unless it has its eye closed, like this T. granulosa does.

description: I believe this is sexually reproductive Lunularia cruciata (dead ringer for these, at least), given the 4-lobed carpocephalum. I didn't notice gemma receptacles on the thalli when I was looking at them, but I think I caught one in a pic (see below). Doyle & Stotler (2006) say sporophytes in this species are rare in CA, known only from two specimens from Marin, so yay? Think I'll go back tomorrow and see if I can get better pics with the macro flash.
place_guess: Huckleberry Botanic Preserve, Oakland, CA, USA

description: Some thalloid liverworts reproduce asexually by producing these little seed-like clones called gemmae, which reside in little cups on the surface of the leaves until splashed out by rain.  This is how Lunularia cruciata usually reproduces around here, and I think this is why you'll often see large swaths of trailcuts covered with the stuff (like at Huckleberry).
place_guess: Huckleberry Botanic Preserve, Oakland, CA, USA

description:
Doyle & Stotler say the carpocephalum has "capsules that dehisce by 4 valves."  I guess that's what the 4 dark things are at the base of the opened capsules.

There's something weird about the distribution of these sexually reproductive plants.  They're only along the west side of the trail by the entrance, when just below them further down the trail there are tons of other Lunularia that aren't producing sporophytes.  I also didn't see anything resembling the pics of antheridiophores, so where are the males that did the fertilizing?
